	url = {https://search.proquest.com/pqdtlocal1005851/docview/1923431784/abstract/C4349E36878F42B8PQ/2},
	abstract = {Mechanical models of planet formation can't fully explain the diversity in observed system architectures found over the last couple of decades. Because stellar photospheres evolve slowly, we can use them as fossil records of the initial conditions in protoplanetary disks.
In Chapter 2 we developed a new spectral analysis procedure to derive surface gravities consistent with those of asteroseismology without the use of external constraints. Compared to a set of 42 Kepler stars with asteroseismically determined log g, our gravities show a constant offset of 0.01 dex and a root mean square (RMS) scatter of 0.05 dex.
In Chapter 3 we used this new procedure to determine the stellar properties and abundances of more than 1600 planet search stars, including 280 known planet hosts. Using a single line list to fit model spectra to observations, we determined effective temperature, surface gravity, metallicity, macroturbulence, projected rotational velocity, absolute radial velocity, and abundances of 15 'elements (C, N, O, Na, Mg, Al, Si, Ca, Ti, V, Cr, Mn, Fe, Ni, \& Y) for all stars. We also found and corrected residual trends in our abundances with respect to Teff. These trends, though small, are shared with published abundances and we identified problems with our model atmosphere grids as the likely cause.
In Chapter 4 we used the abundances in our catalog to constrain the distribution of C/O and Mg/Si ratios for main sequence stars between 4800 K and 6100 K. The C/O ratio peaks at {\textasciitilde} 0.5 and none of the 837 stars has C/O {\textgreater} 0.8. This implies that all planetary systems will form in disks similar to that of the solar system, with the composition of rocky planets determined by the ratio of Mg/Si. About 40\% of the systems have Mg/Si {\textless} 1, which may result in terrestrial planet geology that is very silicon rich compared to rocky planets around the Sun. The remaining 60\% have 1 ≤ Mg/Si {\textless} 2, resulting in geology much like that of the Earth. Known planet hosts have very similar distributions of C/O and Mg/Si to that of the sample as a whole.
In Chapter 5 we compared the carbon to oxygen ratios in hot Jupiter atmospheres to the C/O ratios of their host stars. If the planets formed close to their present locations, the C/O ratios should be nearly the same. If the planets migrated to their current locations after forming and accreting their atmospheres beyond the snow line they should show an enhanced C/O ratio. Though the uncertainties in C/O measurements of hot Jupiter atmospheres are currently too large for precise constraints, the ratios suggest the planets did not form near their host stars. We predict most hot Jupiters formed beyond the snow line and migrated to their current locations.
Chemistry is one of the important initial conditions of planet formation. Our catalog will help place constraints on formation models by identifying differences in abundance patterns between hosts with similar stellar properties but different system architectures. We are excited to be involved in this work and present ideas for future prospects in the field.},
	language = {English},
	urldate = {2021-01-27},
	school = {Yale University},
	author = {Brewer, John Michael},
	year = {2016},
	note = {ISBN: 9781369619089
Publication Title: ProQuest Dissertations and Theses
Section: 0265},
