@phdthesis{schmitt_planet_2017,
	address = {United States -- Connecticut},
	type = {Ph.{D}.},
	title = {Planet {Hunting}: {The} {Search} for {Hidden} {Planets} in the  {Kepler} {Field}},
	copyright = {Database copyright ProQuest LLC; ProQuest does not claim copyright in the individual underlying works.},
	shorttitle = {Planet {Hunting}},
	url = {https://search.proquest.com/pqdtlocal1005851/docview/2023450324/abstract/7BDB28105DF74C8BPQ/1},
	abstract = {The discovery of exoplanets, planets outside of the solar system, has revolutionized astronomy. It has upended our understanding of planet formation and the architecture of planetary systems. Thousands of planets have been discovered to date, the majority of which have been found using data from the Kepler space telescope using the transit technique, which is when the planet transits in front of its host star from the viewpoint of Earth. Current computer algorithms have been highly successful at discovering planets, but they are not fully complete. In this thesis, I search for hidden planets in the Kepler field.
In Chapter 2, I report the discovery of 14 new transiting planet candidates in the Kepler field from the Planet Hunters citizen science program. The new candidates have periods ranging from 121–904 days, eight residing in their host star's habitable zone (HZ) and two (now) in multiple planet systems. I also report the discovery of a seventh planet candidate orbiting KOI-351 (Kepler-90), marking the first and only seven planet candidate system yet discovered outside of our solar system. K01-351 bears some resemblance to a compact version of our own solar system, with the inner five planets ranging from Earth to mini-Neptune radii and the outer planets being gas giants, all of them orbiting [special characters omitted] 1 AU from their host star.
In Chapter 3, I report the discovery of one new confirmed planet ( P = 66.06 days, Rp = 2.68±0.17R ⊕ ) and mass determinations of two previously validated Kepler planets, Kepler-289 b (P = 34.55 days, Rp = 2.15±0.10R⊕) and Kepler-289-c (P = 125.85 days, Rp = 11.59 ± 0.10 R⊕), through their transit timing variations caused by gravitational interactions between the planets. The masses of the inner, middle, and outer planets are measured to be M = 7.3 ± 6.8M⊕, 4.0 ± 0.9M ⊕, and M = 131.5 ± 17.0M ⊕, which I designate PH3 b, c, and d, respectively. The middle planet, PH3 c, has a relatively low density, p = 1.2 ± 0.3 g/cm3 for a planet of its mass, requiring a substantial H/He atmosphere of {\textasciitilde}3\%. It joins the growing population of low-mass, low-density planets, which may help constrain models planetary formation and migration.
In Chapter 4, I present 10 new planet candidates from the extended Kepler mission, K2, and perform high-resolution observations on 75 targets from K2 Campaigns 1-3 using speckle interferometry and adaptive optics imaging. This sample includes 37 stars likely to host planets, 32 targets likely to be eclipsing binaries (EBs), and 6 other targets previously labeled as likely planetary false positives. Six of the nine detected companions are new discoveries. One of the six, EPIC 206061524, is associated with a planet candidate.
In Chapter 5, I examine a sample of 114 stars with 3+ confirmed planets to search for hidden planets due to the Kepler pipeline's "Swiss cheesing" of the light curve. In the pipeline, after a transit signal is found, all data points associated with those transits are removed, creating a "Swiss cheese"-like light curve full of holes, which is then used for subsequent transit searches. A simulation determined that the probability that a transiting planet is lost due to the transit masking is low, but non-neglible, reaching a plateau at {\textasciitilde} 3.3\% lost in the period range of P = 400 – 500 days. We then model the transits in all quarters of each star and subtract out the transit signals, restoring the in-transit data points, and use the Kepler pipeline to search the transit-subtracted (i.e., transit-cleaned) light curves. However, the pipeline did not discover any credible new transit signals. This demonstrates the validity and robustness of the Kepler pipeline's choice to use transit masking over transit subtraction. However, a follow-up visual search through all the transit-subtracted data, which allows for easier visual identification of new transits, reveiled the existence of a new, Neptune-sized exoplanet that transited twice in the Kepler data. Kepler-150 f ( P = 637.2 days, Rp = 3.64+0.52 -0.39 R⊕ is confirmed with {\textgreater} 99.998\% confidence using a combination of the planet multiplicity argument, a false positive probability analysis, and a transit duration analysis.
These new discoveries add to the ever-growing inventory of exoplanets. Much of this work was completed through the citizen science program Planet Hunters, which not only drives public interest in astronomy, but has led to useful scientific discoveries. The two confirmed planets allow for better analyses of exoplanet population statistics, while the long-period planet candidates provide much needed numbers in a sparsely populated region of exoplanet parameter space. Greater discoveries are on the horizon. Future discoveries will require strong support, both publicly and financially, of continued astronomical research.},
	language = {English},
